<section xml:id="section-SOPAC">
    <title>Combinations</title>

    <introduction>
        <p>
            In summary, it can be difficult to distinguish whether to use permutations or combinations to solve a counting problem.
        </p>
        <p>
            The number of ways to choose <m>n</m> objects from <m>n</m> available objects,
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Ordered, with replacement is <m>n^k</m>.</li>
            <li>Ordered, without replacement, is <m>\nPr{n}{k}</m>.</li>
            <li>Unordered, without replacement, is <m>\nCr{n}{k}</m>.</li>
            <li>Unordered, with replacement, is more complicated.</li>
        </ul>
    </introduction>

</section>
